3.4 Feature Specifications
FEATURE 1: Interactive Blogs (Living Documents)
Priority: P0 (Core differentiator — launch feature)

Description: Blog-style articles where the content is a mix of narrative explanation and embedded interactive elements. Not traditional blog posts. Not traditional labs. The hybrid.

Functional Requirements:

ID	Requirement	Details
IB-01	Embedded Terminal	In-article terminal emulator connected to a live container. User can run commands without leaving the page.
IB-02	Inline Challenges	At key points in the article, a challenge box appears: "Now try to exploit the vulnerability we just discussed." User must solve it to proceed (or skip with penalty).
IB-03	Branching Paths	Articles can branch: "Want to see this from the attacker's perspective or the defender's perspective?" Different content renders based on choice.
IB-04	Knowledge Checkpoints	Multiple-choice or short-answer questions embedded in flow. Incorrect answers trigger expanded explanations.
IB-05	Adaptive Depth	User can toggle "Explain Like I'm 5" ↔ "Give me the RFC." Content dynamically adjusts technical depth.
IB-06	Progress Persistence	User can leave and return. Progress saved. Terminal state optionally preserved for 24h.
IB-07	Social Annotations	Users can highlight passages and leave comments/questions visible to others (à la Genius.com or Medium but for security content).
IB-08	Linked Lab	Every Interactive Blog has an associated full lab for deeper practice. "Liked this article? Go deeper in the lab →"
IB-09	Estimated Reading/Doing Time	Show estimated time: "15 min read • 25 min hands-on"
IB-10	Content Tagging	Tags: topic, difficulty, red/blue team, MITRE ATT&CK mapping, career path relevance
Content Categories for Interactive Blogs:

Attack technique deep-dives (with live exploitation)
Tool tutorials (Burp Suite, Wireshark, Nmap, etc.)
Vulnerability case studies (real CVEs, recreated safely)
Defense playbooks (detection rules, IR procedures)
Career guides (how to land SOC analyst role, etc.)
News analysis (major breaches broken down technically)
Technical Implementation:

Frontend: Custom MDX renderer with embedded React components
Terminals: WebSocket connection to isolated Docker containers via a proxy (similar to how Katacoda worked)
Container lifecycle: Spin up on user interaction, auto-terminate after 30min inactivity
Content authoring: Custom CMS with component library (drag-and-drop terminal blocks, challenge blocks, etc.)
FEATURE 2: Adaptive Dynamic Labs (ADL)
Priority: P0 (Core differentiator — launch feature)

Description: Hands-on lab environments where the scenario, vulnerabilities, and flags are procedurally generated per user per session.

Functional Requirements:

ID	Requirement	Details
ADL-01	Dynamic Flag Generation	Flags are unique per user per instance. Format: GV{<dynamic_hash>}. Validated server-side against user session.
ADL-02	Parameterized Vulnerability Injection	Lab templates define vulnerability categories. The engine selects specific vulnerability instances (e.g., "SUID binary" → could be any of 15 different SUID privesc paths).
ADL-03	Difficulty Adaptation	System tracks user's solve rate, time-to-solve, hint usage. Adjusts next lab's complexity within the same topic.
ADL-04	Hint System (Tiered)	3-tier hints: (1) Nudge — "Think about what services are running." (2) Direction — "The web server has a known vulnerability." (3) Walkthrough — Step-by-step. Each tier costs XP.
ADL-05	Multi-Machine Labs	Advanced labs span multiple machines (e.g., pivot from web server → database → domain controller).
ADL-06	Time Tracking	Track time-to-complete. Show user their improvement over time. Feed into leaderboards.
ADL-07	Lab Report Generation	After completion, user can generate a pentest-style report of what they did. Template provided. This becomes a portfolio piece.
ADL-08	Reset / Fresh Instance	User can reset their lab at any time to get a fresh (newly randomized) instance.
ADL-09	Lab Categories	Network Pentesting, Web App Security, Privilege Escalation, Active Directory, Cloud Security (AWS/Azure/GCP), Forensics/DFIR, Reverse Engineering, Malware Analysis, Cryptography, Wireless Security, Mobile Security, IoT Security, SOC/Detection Engineering
ADL-10	Environment Types	Single machine, multi-machine network, full Active Directory domain, cloud environment simulation, containerized microservices
Technical Implementation:

Orchestration: Kubernetes cluster with custom operator for lab lifecycle management
Template System: YAML/JSON lab definitions with randomization parameters
Vulnerability Injection: Ansible playbooks with variable substitution for vulnerability deployment
Flag Engine: Microservice that generates, stores, and validates unique flags
Networking: WireGuard VPN or browser-based access (Apache Guacamole / noVNC)
Cost Management: Auto-shutdown after 2h inactivity, spot instances for non-critical labs
