3.8 Design & UX Principles
Brand Identity
GhostVector — the name evokes stealth (Ghost) and directed purpose (Vector). It suggests precision, sophistication, and an offensive-minded but strategic approach.

Alternative Name Suggestions (only if you want to explore):

NullFrame Academy — "null" (security), "frame" (framework/structure)
RedShift Academy — movement toward the red (offensive), shift (transformation)
CipherPath — encryption + journey
Honestly, GhostVector is strong. It's unique, memorable, domain-available-ish, and sounds like something a cybersecurity professional would respect.
Visual Direction:

Dark mode first (this is non-negotiable for this audience)
Color palette: Deep blacks (#0a0a0a), electric purples (#7c3aed), ghost white (#f8f8ff), terminal green (#00ff41) as accent
Typography: Monospace for code/terminal elements, clean sans-serif (Inter/Geist) for body
Aesthetic: Hacker aesthetic but polished — not 2005-era green-on-black, but modern, clean, with subtle terminal/matrix nods
Motion: Subtle, purposeful animations. Terminal typing effects. Glitch effects on hover (sparingly).
UX Principles
Zero to Hacking in 60 Seconds — New user should be running their first command within 1 minute of signing up. No lengthy onboarding. Show value immediately.
Never Lost — User should always know: where they are, where they're going next, how far they've come.
Fail Forward — When users fail, the platform helps them understand why and guides them to try again. Never a dead end.
Celebrate Progress — Every completion, every milestone, every streak gets acknowledged. People need to feel momentum.
Desktop First, Mobile Aware — Core experience is desktop (you need a real screen for terminals). Mobile for reading blogs, checking progress, community, and notifications.
